The derive right allows the user to apply analysis or other processes to the data, and create new resources. There may be restrictions as to which processes are allowed during the creation of these new resources.
Each association between a condition and a parameter value (entity instance) must be indexed by the name of the parameter in the condition expression before the condition can be evaluated.
The property attribute lists named properties of this entity.
The getProperty operation returns the property descriptor of a particularly named property.
The getPropertyValue operation returns the value of a particularly named property.
The "hasProperty" operation determines if the entity process a particularly named property.

A Data resource is, as the name implies, data. Metadata associated to the Data resources include the owner of the data (for licensing purposes) and any schema information. Other Metadata may also be available. The schema can be used to select parts of a Data resource based on query. These parts can be specified in a license by using conditions equivalent to the selection query.
The "schema" attribute allows the Data resource to specify it structural metadata. All data entities in the resource must have their structure defined in one of the schemas in this list.
Owner interfaces allow principals to create and maintain resources and to grant various licenses associated to the resource.

Each Resource is "owned" or under the complete control of a principal, or some number of principals. Each owner has the right to grant licenses on the resource. This includes a general license to grant other licenses. In a GeoDRM system, all licenses are eventually traceable back through a series of licenses to the owner of the resource.
A licensor is an owner or agent of an owner who has the right to grant licenses of a defined type.
Principal who composed the license. The issuer of a license must have the right to create and grant the license in question. All such rights flow from the owner or from one of his agents.
The view right allows the use to have access to graphic depictions of the data (not normally the resource itself) that allows for visual inspection of the data content.

A right is any act that can access the resource in any manner. Rights are often associated to the process standard that implements them. Right metadata includes any information needed to identify the action that a request may make using this right.
A licensee is a principal in the role of a license owner. Normally, the licensee is the default principal to which rights have been granted by this license.
The members of a group are also principals, and may be groups in their own right.
A principal group is a set of principals acting together in a single role in the system.
A service provider is a principal who supports a service or functionality involved in the GeoDRM system.
Request implemented by a process invocation.
A resource is any data, functionality, or any other entity subject to licensing. A resource metadata must at a minimum identify the resource and be traceable to its owner or an agent of its owner.

The getOwner operation is a convenience function that tracks from this resource to its owner or his agent (a principal of the system). This is used to validate licenses since the licensee must be an agent (or transitive agent) of the owner.
The "Target Resource" association list all resources that would be accessed in any manner by the request if it were to be executed.
The "reourse" role lists all resources addressed by the request.

The execute right allows the user to execute a specified process on a specified set of resources. To execute a process on an information resource, the user must have execute licence for both the process (which specifies which resources it may process) and the information resource (which will specify which processes may be executed on it).
An Agent is a principal acting in another's name. As such an agent must also support the interfaces of his "client", the principal for whom he acts.
The edit right allows the user to copy the original resource and make changes to the data. This is a new resource with a new identity, and is subject to conditions on how rights are granted on it.
The GeoLicense grants rights against digital resources, and has facilities to describe the geographic aspects of these grants.
Principal to whom the licenses was given.
The combine right allows to use to combine the resource with other resources as long as coordinate systems and type are compatible.

Side effects are conditions that cause a logically unrelated action to occur. Such actions are usually required by the contract that the licence represent. The evaluate function, inherited from Condition, will return true if the side effect does not uncover any reason to interrupt the flow. If a side effect has a time set to after the act, i.e. if the effect is to occur on successful completion of the licensed act., the return value of the Condition::evaluate function should always be true.
The attribute "time" is a temporal relation string, relating the side effect action to the licensed act. Common values are "before" or "after."

The attribute "type" is a string describing the side affect action. It acts as instructions to the GeoDRM Gatekeeper to execute the side effect. Normal values include, message to licensor, user message, service call, function call or similar remote invocation technique.

The attribute "request" is a representation of the invocation of the side effect action. If the type is a message, then the request, possibly with parameterized content, could be the content of the message.
The principal abstract class is a concrete single principal, as opposed to a pattern defining a set of principal. It is used wherever a pattern is inappropriate.

The Condition puts further restrictions on the right being granted. For an act to be valid, the Boolean function represented by the condition expression must evaluate to TRUE. This Boolean can test any values in the grant and their associated metadata, any parameters passed with the requests, metadata on the requestor, and on the process being used.

The expression is a logical statement that evaluates to a TRUE, FALSE or INDETERMINATE (should be an error). Each variable in the statement should map to elements or attributes of grants to which this condition is applied, to the resource, to the user making the request, or to the request being made. Evaluation of any of the conditions associated to a right to false or indeterminate will invalidate the use of that licence grant in the given circumstances.

The operation "evaluates" the condition based on the current circumstances presented to the GeoDRM Gatekeeper. The evaluation of any condition associated to a grant would invalidate the use of that grant to authorize an act. The failure of all grants to validate a right to act, would normally cause the GeoDRM Gatekeeper to invalidate the request presented to it.
A license manager is an agent of another able to maintain licenses and to verify those licenses.
Usage rights allow the licensee use the resources to create new resources from the licensed resource.
Edit or modify rights allow the user to modify the resource, and as such are usually granted on "non-identical" copies of a resource. They can modify the resource and retain identity.
A property descriptor entity describes the value of a property. They can be associated to or contained in any item.

A sublicensee is a principal to whom a licensee "lends" his rights for some purpose. The license in question must allow this for the "lending" to be acceptable, and may put conditions on such "loans."
Process invoked through a message oriented protocol.

Principal is the root class of all participants in the systems. Subclasses of Principal can add further information needed to support the role that principal will play in the processes of the GeoDRM system. A group of principals is also a principal, and the group may take actions (such as obtaining a license) which would normally be considered the act of a single entity. In other words, a set of entities is an entity and therefore a set of principals, acting as a unit, is a principal. The basic metadata for any principal is identity, allowing that principal to be uniquely and without significant doubt identified. A principal can have multiple identities, but each identity can only apply to one principal or one principal group.

Condition parameters objects are the bindings of the fully qualified names found in the condition expression. Once the names have been identified and the appropriate values found, they are type cast as parameter classes and evaluated by the operations of the parameter classes.
The invocation name of functions used by the service.
The parameters used in the processes being invoked. If confusion is possible, the full name of the parameter is used, including process-name and parameter-name.

The "Implementation" association list all processes that would be invoked in any manner by the request if it were to be executed. The issuer of the request would have to have rights to the processing targets for the request to be valid. These rights may be granted as part of a public license (i.e. anyone has the right to access the processing resource) or as a more specific license.
Process for revocation of the license.
The "validityInterval" attribute describes the time period for which the license is valid.

This parameter class consist of objects or entity that represent geographic geometry values in the condition. They are of one of the types defined in ISO 19107 (the OGC feature geometry abstract topic volume), some subtype of either GM_Object or TP_Object in that standards
Request implemented by a function call in an API.

A licensee is used in a licence to indicate the actual purchaser of the licence. The grants in the licence will use this principal as the default recipient of each grants. If a grant contains a principal, it overrides the licensee as recipient of the grant.
The spatial transform data right allows the user to take data from a resource and change its coordinate reference system, and thereby create a new resource.

Processing resources are capable of acting on other resources. To use a Processing resource, a principal must have licenses both for the Processing resources and for any Data resources that may be involved. Metadata about the Processing resource may include the implementer of the processing code, and the provider. The metaclass "standard" can further indicate to which standards the resource adheres. Any of this information may be used by conditions in license grants.
The "compliance license" attribute lists proof of compliance to the various standards listed in the "standard" attribute.
The "formal name" is a list of names used in the "standard" attribute list to identify the functionality supplied here.
The "implementor" attribute identifies the implementor of the process represented.
The "local name" attribute specifies which name or alias is actually used by this implementation.
The "provider" attribute identifies the provider of the access to this functionality.
The "standard" attribute lists the various standards that this process adheres to.
A licensing agent is an agent of the owner (or transitively, an agent of another agent) allowed to grant and verify licenses in lieu of the owner.
The derive graphic right allows a user to create a graphic image (usually raster, although vector data is possible) that is a view only representation of some subset of the original resources.
A "Service" is a processing resource providing access through a message oriented interface, such as a web service.

The extract right allows the user to subset a resource to create a new resource, usually a local copy, and always with a new identity. Metadata on the new resource should always trace the ancestry of the data back to the original resource.
A "Process" is a processing resource providing functionality through a application programming interface.
The "language" interface list all programming languages in which the API for the Process may be used.
